name: 5-fluoro-2-methoxybenzyl bromide

Each substituent on the benzene ring can modify this melting point. Methoxy group (OCH3) is weakly polar and electron donating, which might slightly increase the melting point due to a modest increase in molecular weight, let's estimate this as +5°C. The fluoro group is strongly electronegative and increases the polarity of the molecule, it may also participate in dipole-dipole interactions, likely increasing the melting point more than the methoxy group. This effect can be approximated as +20°C. The benzyl bromide moiety (-CH2Br) adds significant molecular weight and bulkiness, which increases the van der Waals interactions and is likely the most significant contributor to an increase in melting point, we will estimate this effect as +40°C.
